vizia B]]\n}}</onlyinclude>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[1975\u201376 Divizia B]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Liga I seasons}}\n{{1975\u201376 in European football (UEFA)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1975-76 Divizia A}}\n[[Category:Liga I seasons]]\n[[Category:1975\u201376 in European association football leagues|Romania]]\n[[Category:1975\u201376 in Romanian football]]\n", "name_user": "Jolicnikola", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLeague table", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1975%E2%80%9376_Divizia_A"}
{"title_page": "Oberhausen-Sterkrade station", "text_new": "{{Infobox station \n| name          = Oberhausen-Sterkrade\n| native_name   = \n| native_name_lang = \n| symbol_location = de\n| symbol         = rail\n| type          =\n| image         = Bahnhof Oberhausen-Sterkrade 02 Empfangsgeb\u00e4ude.JPG\n| image_size    = \n| image_caption =  Oberhausen-Sterkrade station building with tram and bus stop in 2015\n| address       = [[Oberhausen]], [[North Rhine-Westphalia]], Germany\n| coordinates   = {{coord|51|30|42|N|6|50|37|E|region:DE|display=inline,title}}\n| owned         = [[DB Netz]]\n| operator      = [[DB Station&Service]]\n| line          = [[Arnhem-Oberhausen railway]]\n| platform      = 2\n| tracks        = 3\n| code        = {{Deutsche Bahn station codes|code=4651<ref name =categories/>|ds100=EOSD<ref name=Eisenbahnatlas>{{cite book|title=Eisenbahnatlas Deutschland (German railway atlas)| edition=2009/2010 |publisher= Schweers + Wall | year= 2009 |isbn= 978-3-89494-139-0}}</ref>|ibnr=8004542|category=5<ref name =categories>{{DBCatsURL}}</ref>}}\n| opened        = 1 July 1856\n| closed        = \n| website       = [https://www.bahnhof.de/bahnhof-de/Oberhausen-Sterkrade.html www.bahnhof.de]\n| map_type      = North Rhine-Westphalia\n| map_caption   = Location within North Rhine-Westphalia\n| services      = {{s-rail|title=Abellio Deutschland}}\n{{s-line|system=RE-NRW|line=19|previous=Oberhausen-Holten|next=Oberhausen}}\n{{s-line|system=RE-NRW|line=49|previous=Oberhausen-Holten|next=Oberhausen}}\n{{s-rail|title=DB Regio NRW}}\n{{s-line|system=RE-NRW|line=5|previous=Oberhausen-Holten|next=Oberhausen}}\n}}\n\n'''Oberhausen-Sterkrade''' is a railway station in [[Oberhausen]], [[North Rhine-Westphalia]], [[Germany]]. The station opened on 1 July 1856, is located on the [[Arnhem-Oberhausen railway]]. The train services are operated by [[Deutsche Bahn]] and [[Abellio Deutschland]].\n\nIn 1888 the station building from [[K\u00f6ln]]-Kalk was transferred to Sterkrade.<ref>Lindemann p.25</ref> This building was badly damaged during the Second World War, so that a new building had to be erected. This was opened in 1952.<ref>Lindemann p.56</ref> It is currently owned by a private investor.\n\n== Location and layout ==\nOberhausen-Sterkrade station is on the [[Duisburg-Ruhrort\u2013Dortmund railway]] (line 2206, [[Wanne-Eickel Hauptbahnhof]]&nbsp;\u2013 Oberhausen-Sterkrade) and the [[Oberhausen\u2013Arnhem railway]] (line 2270, [[Oberhausen Hauptbahnhof]]&nbsp;\u2013 Emmerich border \u2013 [[Arnhem Centraal railway station|Arnhem]]). The neighbouring stations to the south are Oberhausen Hauptbahnhof (line 2270) and [[Oberhausen-Osterfeld station|Oberhausen-Osterfeld]] (line 2206), while [[Oberhausen-Holten station]] is the next station to the north.\n \nThe station has six mainline tracks that run approximately in a south-north direction. Platform track 1 (to Emmerich) and 2 (from Emmerich) are the continuous mainline platform tracks. Track 3 serves as a passing track. Track 4 is used for traffic to the Oxea factory. Tracks 8 and 9 on the east side are used for parking trains, while a former siding to the GHH wheelset factory is no longer used. The entrance building is located east of platform&nbsp;1. The station is equipped with a platform next to the station building on track&nbsp;1 (172&nbsp;metres long) and an island platform between tracks&nbsp;2 and 3 (222&nbsp;metres long). The platforms are 38&nbsp;centimetres high with the exception of a short, raised area on platform&nbsp;1.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deutschebahn.com/de/geschaefte/infrastruktur/bahnhof/bahnsteige_uebersicht/2235752/bahnsteige_details.html?start=0&rid=4651&c2235748=Oberhausen-Sterkrade&itemsPerPage=20&x=1 |title=Bahnsteiginformationen, Station Oberhausen-Sterkrade |publisher=Deutsche Bahn AG |date=23 September 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923223209/http://www.deutschebahn.com/de/geschaefte/infrastruktur/bahnhof/bahnsteige_uebersicht/2235752/bahnsteige_details.html?start=0&rid=4651&c2235748=Oberhausen-Sterkrade&itemsPerPage=20&x=1 |archive-date=23 September 2015 |url-status=dead |accessdate=2 April 2020|language=de}}</ref> Within the station precinct, Rosastra\u00dfe crosses the tracks to the south over a level crossing.\n \nThe station has two exits: the western one leads to the park-and-ride car park on ''Neum\u00fchler Stra\u00dfe'' in the Schwarze Heide district and the eastern one leads directly to the centre of Sterkrad. The exits can be reached via short ramps next to the stairs, but the island platform can only be reached by stairs so the station is not barrier-free.\n\n== History==\n[[File:Bahnhof Oberhausen-Sterkrade 07 Bahnsteige.JPG|thumb|left|Platforms in Oberhausen-Sterkrade, 2015]]\nThe station was opened with the [[Oberhausen Hauptbahnhof|Oberhausen]]\u2013[[Dinslaken station|Dinslaken]] section of the Oberhausen\u2013Arnhem line on 1&nbsp;July 1856.<ref name=\"Archiv EOSD\">{{cite web|first=Andr\u00e9 |last=Joost |url=http://nrwbahnarchiv.bplaced.net/esn/EOSD.htm |title= Oberhausen-Sterkrade station operations|work=NRW rail archive |language=de | accessdate= 2 April 2020}}</ref> It was built and operated by the [[Cologne-Minden Railway Company]] (''C\u00f6ln-Mindener Eisenbahn-Gesellschaft'', CME), which was nationalised in 1880. The CME put the line between [[Gelsenkirchen|Schalke]] and Sterkrade into operation as part of the line that developed into the [[Duisburg-Ruhrort\u2013Dortmund railway]] (''Emschertalbahn'') on 15&nbsp;November 1873. It was initially used only by freight trains, but passenger trains also ran on it from 1&nbsp;July 1874. The section to [[Duisburg-Ruhrort station|Ruhrort]] was completed a year later, on 1&nbsp;July 1875. Passenger traffic to Ruhrort started on 15&nbsp;October 1875.<ref>{{cite web|first=Andr\u00e9 |last=Joost |url=http://nrwbahnarchiv.bplaced.net/strecken/2206.htm |title=Line 2206: Abzw Bickern \u2013 Meiderich Nord |work=NRW rail archive |language=de | accessdate= 2 April 2020}}</ref> Through trains from Osterfeld to Neum\u00fchl still had to reverse in Sterkrade until 1878.<ref>{{cite web|first=Andr\u00e9 |last=Joost |url=http://nrwbahnarchiv.bplaced.net/strecken/2260.htm |title=Line 2260: Abzw Grafenbusch \u2013 Duisburg-Neum\u00fchl |work=NRW rail archive |language=de | accessdate= 2 April 2020}}</ref>\n \nIn 1888, the station building was moved from the former [[Kalk, Cologne|K\u00f6ln-Kalk]] station to Sterkrade.<ref>{{cite book |first=Alfred |last=Lindemann |title=Chronologie Sterkrade |publisher=Eigenverlag |date=1990 |p=25|language=de}}</ref> The building was 82 percent destroyed in the Second World War. From November 1945 to May 1948, passenger and freight trains ran from Sterkrade via the ''Gutehoffnungsh\u00fctte'' mechanical engineering works to Walsum and then via the [[Oberhausen\u2013Wesel railway|Walsum Railway]] (''Walsumbahn'') to [[Voerde|Spellen]]. This section of the line was no longer connected to the rest of the rail network due to the demolition of two bridges by German troops at the end of the war.<ref name=\"Wuwer 15-21\">\n{{cite book |first=Heinrich|last=Wuwer |publisher=Heimatverein Voerde |title=100 Jahre Hochbahn. Die Eisenbahnlinie Oberhausen \u2013 Hamborn \u2013 Walsum \u2013 M\u00f6llen \u2013 Spellen \u2013 Wesel |location=Voerde |date=2013 |pp=15\u201321|language=de}}</ref> The design of the new entrance building was completed in December 1950. The two storey-high ticket hall would be in the left part of the building, the middle part would comprise the station restaurant and service rooms, while baggage handling would be housed in a flat extension. The building was approved on 4&nbsp;January 1951 and completed the following year.<ref>{{cite book |first=Martin |last=Schack |title=Neue Bahnh\u00f6fe. Empfangsgeb\u00e4ude der Deutschen Bundesbahn 1948\u20131973 |publisher=VBN Verlag B. Neddermeyer |location=Berlin |year=2004 |isbn=3-933254-49-3 |p=140|language=de}}</ref>\n \nThe \"Osf\" [[relay interlocking]] was opened on the ground floor of an annex in 1973.  It replaced three older [[Mechanical interlocking|mechanical signal boxes]]. The station was connected to the [[computer-based interlocking]] at [[Emmerich station|Emmerich]] in June 2013.<ref name=\"Archiv EOSD\" />\n\n== Proposed development==\n[[File:DB 146 019 01 Oberhausen-Sterkrade.JPG|thumb|Departure of the RE5 from Oberhausen-Sterkrade to Koblenz in 2015]]\nAs part of the upgrade of the line to the Netherlands, the station is to be extensively renovated. Two new tracks will be built along the existing line to the south of the station and the connecting curve to Oberhausen-Osterfeld is to be upgraded to include two tracks for freight traffic. The freight tracks are to run to the north of the station. The Rosastra\u00dfe [[level crossing]] is to be replaced by an overpass. Two island platforms with a height of 76&nbsp;centimetres high will replace the existing platforms. Barrier-free access will be provided by ramps at the exits and lifts to the platforms.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emmerich-oberhausen.de/downloads.html?file=files/Downloads/Einleger%20und%20Tabellen%20PFA/Bahn_ABS46_2_1_2_web.pdf |title=Ausbaustrecke Emmerich\u2013Oberhausen. Planfeststellungsabschnitt 1.2 (Oberhausen-Sterkrade) |publisher=[[DB ProjektBau]] |date=May 2013 |language=de | accessdate= 2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Transport services==\nOberhausen-Sterkrade station is served (as of 2020) by the following lines (the [[Wupper-Lippe-Express]] operates on weekdays only):\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! Line\n! Line name\n! Route\n! Frequency\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RE|5}}\n| [[Rhein-Express]]\n| [[Emmerich station|Emmerich]] \u2013 [[Wesel station|Wesel]] \u2013 '''Oberhausen-Sterkrade''' \u2013  [[Duisburg Hauptbahnhof|Duisburg]] \u2013 [[D\u00fcsseldorf Hauptbahnhof|D\u00fcsseldorf]] \u2013 [[K\u00f6ln Hauptbahnhof|Cologne]] \u2013 [[Bonn Hauptbahnhof|Bonn]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Remagen station|Remagen]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Andernach station|Andernach]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Koblenz Hauptbahnhof|Koblenz]]\n| 60 mins\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RE|19}}\n|[[Rhein-IJssel-Express]]\n| [[Arnhem Centraal railway station|Arnhem]] \u2013 Emmerich \u2013 Wesel \u2013 '''Oberhausen-Sterkrade''' \u2013 [[Oberhausen Hauptbahnhof|Oberhausen]] \u2013 Duisburg \u2013 D\u00fcsseldorf\n\n| 60 mins\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RE|49}}\n|[[Wupper-Lippe-Express]]\n| [[Wesel station|Wesel]] \u2013 '''Oberhausen-Sterkrade''' \u2013 [[Oberhausen Hauptbahnhof|Oberhausen]] \u2013 [[M\u00fclheim (Ruhr) Hauptbahnhof|M\u00fclheim]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Essen Hauptbahnhof|Essen]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Wuppertal-Vohwinkel|Wuppertal-Vohwinkel]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Wuppertal Hauptbahnhof|Wuppertal]]\n| 60 mins\n|}\n\n===Buses and tram services===\nThe station is served by numerous bus routes. It is served by tramline 112 on the Oberhausen-Sterkrade, Neumarkt \u2013 '''Oberhausen-Sterkrade Bf''' \u2013 [[Oberhausen Hauptbahnhof]] \u2013 [[M\u00fclheim]] \u2013 Hauptfriedhof route.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of railway stations in North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n\n==References==\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* Alfred Lindemann: ''Chronologie Sterkrade'' published by the author\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.bahnhof.de/?lang=en#station/20222 |title=Oberhausen-Sterkrade station| publisher=[[Deutsche Bahn]] |language=German |accessdate=7 July 2013}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oberhausen-Sterkrade}}\n[[Category:Railway stations in North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:Sterkrade]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1856]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox station \n| name          = Oberhausen-Sterkrade\n| native_name   = \n| native_name_lang = \n| symbol_location = de\n| symbol         = rail\n| type          =\n| image         = Bahnhof Oberhausen-Sterkrade 02 Empfangsgeb\u00e4ude.JPG\n| image_size    = \n| image_caption =  Oberhausen-Sterkrade station building with tram and bus stop in 2015\n| address       = [[Oberhausen]], [[North Rhine-Westphalia]], Germany\n| coordinates   = {{coord|51|30|42|N|6|50|37|E|region:DE|display=inline,title}}\n| owned         = [[DB Netz]]\n| operator      = [[DB Station&Service]]\n| line          = [[Arnhem-Oberhausen railway]]\n| platform      = 2\n| tracks        = 3\n| opened        = 1 July 1856\n| closed        = \n| website       = [https://www.bahnhof.de/bahnhof-de/Oberhausen-Sterkrade.html www.bahnhof.de]\n| map_type      = North Rhine-Westphalia\n| map_caption   = Location within North Rhine-Westphalia\n| services      = {{s-rail|title=Abellio Deutschland}}\n{{s-line|system=RE-NRW|line=19|previous=Oberhausen-Holten|next=Oberhausen}}\n{{s-line|system=RE-NRW|line=49|previous=Oberhausen-Holten|next=Oberhausen}}\n{{s-rail|title=DB Regio NRW}}\n{{s-line|system=RE-NRW|line=5|previous=Oberhausen-Holten|next=Oberhausen}}\n}}\n\n'''Oberhausen-Sterkrade''' is a railway station in [[Oberhausen]], [[North Rhine-Westphalia]], [[Germany]]. The station opened on 1 July 1856, is located on the [[Arnhem-Oberhausen railway]]. The train services are operated by [[Deutsche Bahn]] and [[Abellio Deutschland]].\n\nIn 1888 the station building from [[K\u00f6ln]]-Kalk was transferred to Sterkrade.<ref>Lindemann p.25</ref> This building was badly damaged during the Second World War, so that a new building had to be erected. This was opened in 1952.<ref>Lindemann p.56</ref> It is currently owned by a private investor.\n\n== Location and layout ==\nOberhausen-Sterkrade station is on the [[Duisburg-Ruhrort\u2013Dortmund railway]] (line 2206, [[Wanne-Eickel Hauptbahnhof]]&nbsp;\u2013 Oberhausen-Sterkrade) and the [[Oberhausen\u2013Arnhem railway]] (line 2270, [[Oberhausen Hauptbahnhof]]&nbsp;\u2013 Emmerich border \u2013 [[Arnhem Centraal railway station|Arnhem]]). The neighbouring stations to the south are Oberhausen Hauptbahnhof (line 2270) and [[Oberhausen-Osterfeld station|Oberhausen-Osterfeld]] (line 2206), while [[Oberhausen-Holten station]] is the next station to the north.\n \nThe station has six mainline tracks that run approximately in a south-north direction. Platform track 1 (to Emmerich) and 2 (from Emmerich) are the continuous mainline platform tracks. Track 3 serves as a passing track. Track 4 is used for traffic to the Oxea factory. Tracks 8 and 9 on the east side are used for parking trains, while a former siding to the GHH wheelset factory is no longer used. The entrance building is located east of platform&nbsp;1. The station is equipped with a platform next to the station building on track&nbsp;1 (172&nbsp;metres long) and an island platform between tracks&nbsp;2 and 3 (222&nbsp;metres long). The platforms are 38&nbsp;centimetres high with the exception of a short, raised area on platform&nbsp;1.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deutschebahn.com/de/geschaefte/infrastruktur/bahnhof/bahnsteige_uebersicht/2235752/bahnsteige_details.html?start=0&rid=4651&c2235748=Oberhausen-Sterkrade&itemsPerPage=20&x=1 |title=Bahnsteiginformationen, Station Oberhausen-Sterkrade |publisher=Deutsche Bahn AG |date=23 September 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923223209/http://www.deutschebahn.com/de/geschaefte/infrastruktur/bahnhof/bahnsteige_uebersicht/2235752/bahnsteige_details.html?start=0&rid=4651&c2235748=Oberhausen-Sterkrade&itemsPerPage=20&x=1 |archive-date=23 September 2015 |url-status=dead |accessdate=2 April 2020|language=de}}</ref> Within the station precinct, Rosastra\u00dfe crosses the tracks to the south over a level crossing.\n \nThe station has two exits: the western one leads to the park-and-ride car park on ''Neum\u00fchler Stra\u00dfe'' in the Schwarze Heide district and the eastern one leads directly to the centre of Sterkrad. The exits can be reached via short ramps next to the stairs, but the island platform can only be reached by stairs so the station is not barrier-free.\n\n== History==\n[[File:Bahnhof Oberhausen-Sterkrade 07 Bahnsteige.JPG|thumb|left|Platforms in Oberhausen-Sterkrade, 2015]]\nThe station was opened with the [[Oberhausen Hauptbahnhof|Oberhausen]]\u2013[[Dinslaken station|Dinslaken]] section of the Oberhausen\u2013Arnhem line on 1&nbsp;July 1856.<ref name=\"Archiv EOSD\">{{cite web|first=Andr\u00e9 |last=Joost |url=http://nrwbahnarchiv.bplaced.net/esn/EOSD.htm |title= Oberhausen-Sterkrade station operations|work=NRW rail archive |language=de | accessdate= 2 April 2020}}</ref> It was built and operated by the [[Cologne-Minden Railway Company]] (''C\u00f6ln-Mindener Eisenbahn-Gesellschaft'', CME), which was nationalised in 1880. The CME put the line between [[Gelsenkirchen|Schalke]] and Sterkrade into operation as part of the line that developed into the [[Duisburg-Ruhrort\u2013Dortmund railway]] (''Emschertalbahn'') on 15&nbsp;November 1873. It was initially used only by freight trains, but passenger trains also ran on it from 1&nbsp;July 1874. The section to [[Duisburg-Ruhrort station|Ruhrort]] was completed a year later, on 1&nbsp;July 1875. Passenger traffic to Ruhrort started on 15&nbsp;October 1875.<ref>{{cite web|first=Andr\u00e9 |last=Joost |url=http://nrwbahnarchiv.bplaced.net/strecken/2206.htm |title=Line 2206: Abzw Bickern \u2013 Meiderich Nord |work=NRW rail archive |language=de | accessdate= 2 April 2020}}</ref> Through trains from Osterfeld to Neum\u00fchl still had to reverse in Sterkrade until 1878.<ref>{{cite web|first=Andr\u00e9 |last=Joost |url=http://nrwbahnarchiv.bplaced.net/strecken/2260.htm |title=Line 2260: Abzw Grafenbusch \u2013 Duisburg-Neum\u00fchl |work=NRW rail archive |language=de | accessdate= 2 April 2020}}</ref>\n \nIn 1888, the station building was moved from the former [[Kalk, Cologne|K\u00f6ln-Kalk]] station to Sterkrade.<ref>{{cite book |first=Alfred |last=Lindemann |title=Chronologie Sterkrade |publisher=Eigenverlag |date=1990 |p=25|language=de}}</ref> The building was 82 percent destroyed in the Second World War. From November 1945 to May 1948, passenger and freight trains ran from Sterkrade via the ''Gutehoffnungsh\u00fctte'' mechanical engineering works to Walsum and then via the [[Oberhausen\u2013Wesel railway|Walsum Railway]] (''Walsumbahn'') to [[Voerde|Spellen]]. This section of the line was no longer connected to the rest of the rail network due to the demolition of two bridges by German troops at the end of the war.<ref name=\"Wuwer 15-21\">\n{{cite book |first=Heinrich|last=Wuwer |publisher=Heimatverein Voerde |title=100 Jahre Hochbahn. Die Eisenbahnlinie Oberhausen \u2013 Hamborn \u2013 Walsum \u2013 M\u00f6llen \u2013 Spellen \u2013 Wesel |location=Voerde |date=2013 |pp=15\u201321|language=de}}</ref> The design of the new entrance building was completed in December 1950. The two storey-high ticket hall would be in the left part of the building, the middle part would comprise the station restaurant and service rooms, while baggage handling would be housed in a flat extension. The building was approved on 4&nbsp;January 1951 and completed the following year.<ref>{{cite book |first=Martin |last=Schack |title=Neue Bahnh\u00f6fe. Empfangsgeb\u00e4ude der Deutschen Bundesbahn 1948\u20131973 |publisher=VBN Verlag B. Neddermeyer |location=Berlin |year=2004 |isbn=3-933254-49-3 |p=140|language=de}}</ref>\n \nThe \"Osf\" [[relay interlocking]] was opened on the ground floor of an annex in 1973.  It replaced three older [[Mechanical interlocking|mechanical signal boxes]]. The station was connected to the [[computer-based interlocking]] at [[Emmerich station|Emmerich]] in June 2013.<ref name=\"Archiv EOSD\" />\n\n== Proposed development==\n[[File:DB 146 019 01 Oberhausen-Sterkrade.JPG|thumb|Departure of the RE5 from Oberhausen-Sterkrade to Koblenz in 2015]]\nAs part of the upgrade of the line to the Netherlands, the station is to be extensively renovated. Two new tracks will be built along the existing line to the south of the station and the connecting curve to Oberhausen-Osterfeld is to be upgraded to include two tracks for freight traffic. The freight tracks are to run to the north of the station. The Rosastra\u00dfe [[level crossing]] is to be replaced by an overpass. Two island platforms with a height of 76&nbsp;centimetres high will replace the existing platforms. Barrier-free access will be provided by ramps at the exits and lifts to the platforms.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emmerich-oberhausen.de/downloads.html?file=files/Downloads/Einleger%20und%20Tabellen%20PFA/Bahn_ABS46_2_1_2_web.pdf |title=Ausbaustrecke Emmerich\u2013Oberhausen. Planfeststellungsabschnitt 1.2 (Oberhausen-Sterkrade) |publisher=[[DB ProjektBau]] |date=May 2013 |language=de | accessdate= 2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Transport services==\nOberhausen-Sterkrade station is served (as of 2020) by the following lines (the [[Wupper-Lippe-Express]] operates on weekdays only):\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! Line\n! Line name\n! Route\n! Frequency\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RE|5}}\n| [[Rhein-Express]]\n| [[Emmerich station|Emmerich]] \u2013 [[Wesel station|Wesel]] \u2013 '''Oberhausen-Sterkrade''' \u2013  [[Duisburg Hauptbahnhof|Duisburg]] \u2013 [[D\u00fcsseldorf Hauptbahnhof|D\u00fcsseldorf]] \u2013 [[K\u00f6ln Hauptbahnhof|Cologne]] \u2013 [[Bonn Hauptbahnhof|Bonn]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Remagen station|Remagen]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Andernach station|Andernach]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Koblenz Hauptbahnhof|Koblenz]]\n| 60 mins\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RE|19}}\n|[[Rhein-IJssel-Express]]\n| [[Arnhem Centraal railway station|Arnhem]] \u2013 Emmerich \u2013 Wesel \u2013 '''Oberhausen-Sterkrade''' \u2013 [[Oberhausen Hauptbahnhof|Oberhausen]] \u2013 Duisburg \u2013 D\u00fcsseldorf\n\n| 60 mins\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RE|49}}\n|[[Wupper-Lippe-Express]]\n| [[Wesel station|Wesel]] \u2013 '''Oberhausen-Sterkrade''' \u2013 [[Oberhausen Hauptbahnhof|Oberhausen]] \u2013 [[M\u00fclheim (Ruhr) Hauptbahnhof|M\u00fclheim]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Essen Hauptbahnhof|Essen]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Wuppertal-Vohwinkel|Wuppertal-Vohwinkel]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Wuppertal Hauptbahnhof|Wuppertal]]\n| 60 mins\n|}\n\n===Buses and tram services===\nThe station is served by numerous bus routes. It is served by tramline 112 on the Oberhausen-Sterkrade, Neumarkt \u2013 '''Oberhausen-Sterkrade Bf''' \u2013 [[Oberhausen Hauptbahnhof]] \u2013 [[M\u00fclheim]] \u2013 Hauptfriedhof route.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of railway stations in North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n\n==References==\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* Alfred Lindemann: ''Chronologie Sterkrade'' published by the author\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.bahnhof.de/?lang=en#station/20222 |title=Oberhausen-Sterkrade station| publisher=[[Deutsche Bahn]] |language=German |accessdate=7 July 2013}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oberhausen-Sterkrade}}\n[[Category:Railway stations in North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:Sterkrade]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1856]]\n", "name_user": "Grahamec", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oberhausen-Sterkrade_station"}
